  "opinion": "As an electrician in Kansas City with a vocational diploma and a background shaped by parents who only went as far as primary and upper secondary school, I've seen firsthand how stereotype threat can silently undermine potential in STEM fields. Stereotype threat isn't just a theory—it's the weight of expectations that makes someone doubt their abilities when they're in a space where they're told they don't belong. For me, it's the feeling of being judged not for my skills but for the label 'woman in tech.' Growing up in a community where many people believe women aren't naturally suited for hands-on work like electrical systems, I've carried that doubt into my career. I've noticed it in the way colleagues dismiss my suggestions or the extra time I spend verifying my work because I worry about being 'less competent.' Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. Instead of top-down programs that feel like they're trying to 'fix' people, we need to create environments where everyone feels seen and valued for their specific contributions. In my shop, I've started by openly sharing my own struggles with imposter syndrome—this has helped others feel less alone. Small talk about how we all have moments of self-doubt can break down barriers faster than any lecture. And when we acknowledge that stereotype threat is a real, emotional burden, not just a cognitive bias, it becomes something we can work with, not something we ignore. My depression has made me hyper-aware of how much mental health impacts our ability to engage with these issues, so I've also been advocating for more mental health support in technical fields. Addressing stereotype threat isn't about changing people—it's about changing the culture so that everyone feels safe to contribute without fear of judgment. That's how we build real change.",
